---
import Base from "~/layouts/Base.astro";
import Section from "~/components/Section.astro";
import Callout from "~/components/Callout.astro";
import Card from "~/components/Card.astro";
import Hand from "~/components/Hand.astro";
import RuleCard from "~/components/RuleCard.astro";
import Toc from "~/components/Toc.astro";

const toc = [
  { id: "overview", label: "Overview" },
  { id: "components", label: "Components" },
  { id: "objective", label: "Objective" },
  { id: "setup", label: "Setup" },
  { id: "opening", label: "Opening peek" },
  { id: "turn", label: "Turn structure" },
  { id: "values", label: "Card values" },
  { id: "activatable", label: "Activatable cards" },
  { id: "matching", label: "Matching out of turn" },
  { id: "penalties", label: "Penalties" },
  { id: "cambio", label: "Calling Cambio" },
  { id: "etiquette", label: "Etiquette" },
  { id: "examples", label: "Worked examples" },
];

const values = [
  { card: "Joker", value: "−1", note: "Lowest card in the game.", suit: "joker", rank: "JOKER" },
  { card: "Black King (♠ ♣)", value: "0", note: "The patron saint of late-game miracles.", suit: "spades", rank: "K" },
  { card: "Ace", value: "1", note: "", suit: "hearts", rank: "A" },
  { card: "2 – 10", value: "Face value", note: "Pip cards score what they show.", suit: "diamonds", rank: "5" },
  { card: "Jack", value: "11", note: "", suit: "clubs", rank: "J" },
  { card: "Queen", value: "12", note: "", suit: "hearts", rank: "Q" },
  { card: "Red King (♥ ♦)", value: "13", note: "The most expensive card you can hold.", suit: "diamonds", rank: "K" },
];
---

<Base title="Cambio — Full rules">
  <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 pt-20 pb-10">
    <div class="eyebrow filigree">The rules</div>
    <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl text-[var(--color-gold-50)] mt-4 leading-tight">How to play Cambio</h1>
    <p class="mt-4 text-[var(--color-ivory)]/85 max-w-2xl text-lg leading-relaxed">
      A complete, reorganised guide to the modern game — from setup and turn structure to the
      finer art of out-of-turn matching, penalties, and table etiquette.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 grid lg:grid-cols-[220px_1fr] gap-12">
    <aside class="hidden lg:block"><Toc items={toc} /></aside>

    <article>
      <Section id="overview" eyebrow="The shape of the game" title="Overview">
        <p>
          Cambio is a draw-and-discard game for two or more players (best with four to six). Each
          player keeps a small face-down array of cards and tries, round after round, to hold the
          lowest possible total when someone declares the round over. Points accumulate across
          rounds; the game ends when any player crosses one of two thresholds.
        </p>
        <p>
          The game rewards memory, attention, and an instinct for when a known hand is good
          enough — and punishes the opposite of all three.
        </p>
      </Section>

      <Section id="components" eyebrow="What you'll need" title="Components">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>2 or more players</strong>, optimally <strong>4–6</strong>.</li>
          <li>An unmarked, regular <strong>52-card deck with both jokers</strong>.</li>
          <li>For every multiple of six players, add an additional deck.</li>
        </ul>
      </Section>

      <Section id="objective" eyebrow="What you're trying to do" title="Objective">
        <p>
          Before each round ends, achieve the lowest scoring hand on the board. Points accumulate
          round to round.
        </p>
        <p>
          The game ends when any player crosses one of two thresholds:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>More than 74 points</strong> (i.e. 75+), or</li>
          <li><strong>Fewer than −9 points</strong> (i.e. −10 or lower).</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Naming a single "winner" is optional. Some groups treat the player who first reaches
          +75 as the loser; others simply use the running scores as a ranking. House rules apply.
        </p>
        <Callout variant="tip" title="Why memory matters">
          Most of your decisions in Cambio are about other people's cards as much as your own.
          Tracking what each opponent has seen, swapped, or matched is half the game.
        </Callout>
      </Section>

      <Section id="setup" eyebrow="Before the first card is played" title="Setup">
        <p>
          Shuffle thoroughly. Deal four cards face down to each player in a vertical 2×2 grid.
          Place the remaining deck in the centre of the table; the discard pile will form
          alongside it as soon as cards begin to be played.
        </p>
        <div class="not-prose my-8 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-10 justify-center">
          <div class="text-center">
            <Hand size="md" faceDown={true} />
            <div class="eyebrow mt-3">Your array</div>
          </div>
          <div class="text-center">
            <div class="inline-flex gap-2 items-end">
              <Card faceDown rank="A" suit="spades" size="md" rotate={-3} />
              <Card faceDown rank="A" suit="spades" size="md" rotate={2} />
            </div>
            <div class="eyebrow mt-3">Deck &nbsp;·&nbsp; Discard</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>
          Before play begins, each player may freely rearrange their own four cards — provided
          they don't move a card whose identity they already know (e.g. a card glimpsed during
          the deal, or one with a recognisable scuff). Rearranging is in the spirit of
          autonomous luck, not information laundering.
        </p>
      </Section>

      <Section id="opening" eyebrow="The single permitted glance" title="Opening peek">
        <p>
          Before the first card is played, every player looks at their own <strong>bottom two cards</strong>.
          Until the first card hits the discard pile you may peek as often as you like; once play
          starts, no more free peeks.
        </p>
        <p>
          Play proceeds clockwise. The most recent winner — of the last round, or of the last
          full game when starting fresh — goes first. If this is your group's first ever game,
          play begins to the left of the dealer.
        </p>
        <Callout variant="tip" title="First-player offset">
          To compensate for first-player advantage, the player who opens each round may only
          draw from the deck (there is no discard pile yet). Their discard becomes the first
          face-up card available to the next player.
        </Callout>
      </Section>

      <Section id="turn" eyebrow="Three things you can do" title="Turn structure">
        <p>On your turn, choose exactly one of three operations:</p>
        <div class="not-prose grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-5 my-6">
          {[
            { n: "1", t: "Draw from the deck", b: "Look at the top card. Either swap it into your array (discarding the displaced card face-up) or simply discard it." },
            { n: "2", t: "Take the top discard", b: "Take the face-up top card of the discard pile and swap it into your array. Available only if the pile has cards." },
            { n: "3", t: "Call Cambio", b: "Knock to end the round for yourself. You skip your final exchange; everyone else gets one more turn." },
          ].map((o) => (
            <div
              class="rounded-xl p-5"
              style="background: color-mix(in oklab, var(--color-felt-700) 35%, transparent); border:1px solid color-mix(in oklab, var(--color-gold-400) 22%, transparent);"
            >
              <div class="font-display text-[var(--color-gold-400)] text-2xl mb-1">{o.n}</div>
              <div class="font-display text-[var(--color-gold-50)] mb-1.5">{o.t}</div>
              <p class="text-[var(--color-ivory)]/85 text-[0.95rem] leading-relaxed m-0">{o.b}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
        <p>
          Card "activations" only trigger when a card is drawn <em>from the deck</em> and placed
          <em>directly</em> into the discard pile — never when you take a card from the discard,
          and never on the card you swap out of your array.
        </p>
        <Callout variant="misplay">
          When you draw from the deck or the discard and exchange it for a card in your array,
          the card you displace is just discarded. It does <strong>not</strong> activate, even if
          it happens to be a 7, 9, Jack, Queen, or Red King.
        </Callout>
      </Section>

      <Section id="values" eyebrow="The point chart" title="Card values">
        <div class="not-prose overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-[color-mix(in_oklab,var(--color-gold-400)_25%,transparent)]">
          <table class="w-full text-left">
            <thead>
              <tr class="bg-[color-mix(in_oklab,var(--color-gold-400)_15%,transparent)]">
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-display tracking-[0.15em] text-xs text-[var(--color-gold-200)]">Card</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-display tracking-[0.15em] text-xs text-[var(--color-gold-200)]">Value</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-display tracking-[0.15em] text-xs text-[var(--color-gold-200)] hidden sm:table-cell">Notes</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3"></th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-[var(--color-ivory)]">
              {values.map((v, i) => (
                <tr class={i % 2 ? "bg-[color-mix(in_oklab,var(--color-felt-700)_25%,transparent)]" : ""}>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">{v.card}</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3 font-display text-[var(--color-gold-50)] text-lg">{v.value}</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3 text-[var(--color-ivory)]/80 text-sm hidden sm:table-cell">{v.note}</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3"><Card rank={v.rank as any} suit={v.suit as any} size="xs" tilt={false} /></td>
                </tr>
              ))}
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-6">
          A pristine winning hand is therefore something like Joker, Joker, Black King, Black
          King — a ghostly <strong>−2</strong>. Most rounds end somewhere between 4 and 15.
        </p>
      </Section>

      <Section id="activatable" eyebrow="Power cards" title="Activatable cards">
        <p>
          Five card types do something special when drawn from the deck and placed directly into
          the discard pile. Each effect resolves before play continues.
        </p>

        <div class="not-prose space-y-5 my-8">
          <RuleCard title="Seven or Eight" rank="7" suit="diamonds" rankAlt="8" suitAlt="clubs" value="Know your fate" tagline="Look at one card from your own array.">
            Pick up one of your own face-down cards, look at it privately, and return it to its
            place. Use this to confirm what you've forgotten or to verify a swap.
          </RuleCard>
          <RuleCard title="Nine or Ten" rank="9" suit="spades" rankAlt="10" suitAlt="hearts" value="Know a friend" tagline="Look at one card from another player's array.">
            Choose any opponent. Look privately at one of their cards, then return it. Especially
            powerful late in the round when other players have already shown their hands.
          </RuleCard>
          <RuleCard title="Any Jack" rank="J" suit="clubs" value="Blind swap" tagline="Swap any two cards on the table without looking at either.">
            Pick any two cards anywhere on the table — yours, theirs, mixed — and swap them.
            Neither card is revealed to anyone. Useful for sabotaging a known low hand or
            unloading a Red King you've been stuck with.
          </RuleCard>
          <RuleCard title="Any Queen" rank="Q" suit="hearts" value="Look-then-blind-swap" tagline="Look at one card on the table, then blind-swap it with any other card.">
            Choose one card anywhere on the table and look at it. Then, without further looking,
            swap it with any other card you choose. You may only look at one card per Queen.
          </RuleCard>
          <RuleCard title="Red King" rank="K" suit="hearts" value="Forced exchange (optional)" tagline="Choose two other players; they each pick a card from their array to exchange with one another.">
            The dramatic one. You name two opponents and they trade one card each — chosen
            blindly from their own arrays. Resolving a Red King's effect is <em>optional</em>;
            you may decline.
          </RuleCard>
        </div>

        <Callout variant="tip">
          Activations resolve immediately when the card is discarded. With a Queen mid-action,
          finish the look-and-swap before any other player attempts to match the discard.
        </Callout>
      </Section>

      <Section id="matching" eyebrow="The fastest play in the game" title="Matching out of turn (sticking)">
        <p>
          At any point — except while a player is in the middle of a swap — <strong>any player</strong>
          may attempt to match the top card of the discard pile by playing a card of the same
          rank from the table. This is sometimes called <em>sticking</em>.
        </p>
        <h3>What a successful match does</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            If you match with one of your own cards, that card joins the discard pile and
            <strong> you do not replace it</strong>. Your array shrinks by one.
          </li>
          <li>
            If you match with another player's card, you <strong>transfer one of your own cards
            into their array</strong> in the empty slot you just created. Your array shrinks; theirs
            stays the same size but gains an unknown card.
          </li>
          <li>You may never match directly from the deck.</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>What is matchable</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>The card the current player just discarded — including by the current player themselves.</li>
          <li>Kings of either colour. Note: if a Red King covers a Black King, the Black King is buried until shuffled back in.</li>
          <li>
            Multiple attempts on the same discard <em>by the same player</em>, provided previous attempts
            were genuine and penalties were paid. A misremembered location does not bar a second try.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <h3>What is not matchable</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Any card already covered or removed by play in progress. Matches must physically match the top of the pile.</li>
          <li>Matches by players who currently hold more than one card in hand, or by players actively trading.</li>
          <li>A discard that has already been successfully matched in this lifetime.</li>
        </ul>

        <Callout variant="misplay">
          A card matched on top of a discard does not itself become matchable — the new top
          card has been "claimed". Likewise, taking the top of the discard pile into your array
          does not revive the card beneath it.
        </Callout>

        <Callout variant="tip" title="Speed is the whole point">
          Each discarded card may be matched <strong>at most once</strong>. If two players reach
          for it, the faster hand wins; the slower one keeps their card.
        </Callout>
      </Section>

      <Section id="penalties" eyebrow="When things go wrong" title="Penalties">
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Failed match:</strong> if you put down a wrong card while attempting to
            match, replace it in your array and <strong>draw a new card from the deck</strong>
            to add to your array as a penalty.
          </li>
          <li>
            You may keep the location of your failed match secret — you are not forced to
            reveal it to the table. Of course, anyone watching closely should already know it.
          </li>
          <li>
            If cards are revealed (deliberately or accidentally) all players are entitled to use
            that information for the rest of the game.
          </li>
          <li>
            If you make a genuine match attempt but another player succeeds first, there is no
            penalty — except that the other players now know one of your cards.
          </li>
          <li>
            A partial attempt that doesn't fully reveal the card carries no penalty if you don't
            yourself look at it. Feinting matches to mislead opponents is permissible (though
            don't be disruptive).
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Two-handed play</strong> and <strong>holding more than one card at a time</strong>
            (except while swapping) earn a penalty card at the table's discretion.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </Section>

      <Section id="cambio" eyebrow="Ending the round" title="Calling Cambio">
        <p>
          On your turn, instead of drawing, you may declare <strong>"Cambio"</strong> (or simply
          knock the table). You forfeit the rest of your turn. Each remaining player takes one
          last turn, then everyone reveals their array and totals are scored.
        </p>
        <p>
          You cannot call Cambio out of turn. The call must be made before you touch the deck.
        </p>
        <Callout variant="tip" title="When to knock">
          Calling Cambio is most valuable when (a) your known hand is genuinely low, (b) at
          least one opponent has visibly large unknowns, and (c) your last-turn replacements
          are unlikely to drop your score further than someone else's last turn might drop
          theirs.
        </Callout>
      </Section>

      <Section id="etiquette" eyebrow="Conventions of the table" title="Etiquette">
        <ol>
          <li>Cambio is played with <strong>one hand</strong> (ambidextrous players excepted).</li>
          <li>You may only ever hold <strong>one card in one hand</strong> at any time, except in the act of swapping two cards.</li>
          <li>
            When discarding from your grid, all players must see the card <strong>at the same
            time</strong>. Best practice: flip the card away from yourself, picking it up by
            the far edge, or hold it face-down until it is directly above the discard pile and
            flip it in the air.
          </li>
          <li><strong>House rules trump generic etiquette.</strong></li>
          <li>Cards are not to be thrown.</li>
          <li>
            In disputes, neutral players or third parties adjudicate. When two players reach for
            the same card, basic respect for card condition trumps speed; uninvolved players may
            be consulted.
          </li>
          <li>If a serious disturbance scrambles the round (a flipped table, a flying card),
          the players may vote by majority to reset the round.</li>
          <li>
            It is not illegal to attempt to match a card you don't fully know. Read risk versus
            reward. For players whose arrays have ballooned to seven or more cards, consider a
            cap on consecutive guesses or an instant-loss penalty — particularly when other
            players are baiting matches just to leak information.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Tabletalk</strong> is hazardous. With every player chasing the lowest score,
            it's easy to gang up on the player with one card left. References to specific
            placements and values lie outside conventional play; keep banter abstract.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </Section>

      <Section id="examples" eyebrow="Putting it together" title="Worked examples">
        <h3>1. Pocket sixes, then an ace</h3>
        <p>
          The round begins. Looking at your bottom two cards, you find a pair of sixes. On your
          turn you draw an Ace from the deck and exchange it with one of your sixes. You may
          immediately attempt to match the other six off the discard — provided you don't end
          up holding both cards in one hand.
        </p>
        <p>
          But matching isn't always optimal. Suppose your known hand is an Ace and a 2 and you
          draw another Ace. You could exchange Ace-for-Ace and stick the matched Ace, leaving
          you with three known points — or you could exchange the new Ace for your 3, dropping
          your total by one extra point relative to the match. As the last move of the game,
          the latter is superior; the discarded Ace will sit there for the next player anyway.
        </p>

        <h3>2. The Jack-on-Jack open</h3>
        <p>
          You opened the round knowing one of your cards is a Jack. You draw — another Jack. You
          may discard the new Jack and immediately match it with the Jack from your grid. This
          is legal because matches may happen at any time during any player's turn, except
          while a player is mid-trade. That rule exists mostly for Queens: if you draw a Queen,
          discard it, and then look at another player's card and discover it is also a Queen,
          you must <strong>finish the swap</strong> before you may attempt to match the two
          Queens.
        </p>

        <h3>3. Down to one card</h3>
        <p>
          You've matched three of your four starting cards and avoided every penalty. You may
          never have <strong>zero</strong> cards in your array. If you successfully match your
          last card, you must immediately draw a fresh card from the deck to refill it. This can
          be a gift: in the final round, if your sole card is a Red King, matching it with
          another Red King guarantees your score will not increase — though you won't yet know
          how much you've improved.
        </p>
      </Section>
    </article>
  </div>
</Base>
